{
  "query": "What are the effects on butterfly and moth communities of opening up forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning?",
  "relevant_summary": "Opening forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning has mixed effects on butterfly and moth communities. Clearing or opening patches in forests generally increases butterfly species richness and abundance but can decrease moth species richness (Action ID 3938). Studies found higher butterfly abundance and species richness in cleared patches compared to unmanaged forest, with 19 out of 67 butterfly species of conservation concern benefiting from small forest clearings. However, wider woodland rides had lower moth abundance than standard width rides or mature forest.\n\nCoppicing woodland typically increases butterfly abundance and species richness while potentially reducing macro-moth abundance compared to mature forest (Action ID 3939). Coppiced woodlands supported higher abundance of butterflies generally and heath fritillary specifically, as well as eastern eggar moth caterpillars. Different aged coppice supported different butterfly and moth communities, though macro-moth species richness did not change with coppice age.\n\nThinning trees within forests increases both butterfly species richness and abundance (Action ID 3940). Coniferous woodlands that had been thinned, sometimes with prescribed burning or mulching, showed greater butterfly species richness and abundance compared to unmanaged woodland. One study found that partially-cleared forest plots had higher butterfly species richness but lower moth species richness than closed-canopy forest.\n\nUsing thinning instead of clearcutting generally maintains moth species richness better than other harvesting methods (Action ID 3868). A controlled study found macro-moth species richness was higher after thinning than after patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to unharvested forest.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3938",
    "3940",
    "3939",
    "3868"
  ]
}

