{
  "query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from US prairies shows different outcomes for butterfly populations between rotational burning and leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires. Rotational burning studies found mixed effects - some showed higher butterfly abundance on prairies burned 2-4 years ago compared to recently burned areas, while others found rotational burning every 2-5 years resulted in higher abundance than unmanaged sites. However, some prairie specialist butterflies were less abundant under rotational burning, and three fritillary species showed lower abundance in rotationally burned prairies compared to hayed or grazed prairies. For unburned patches, studies specifically found that Karner blue butterfly abundance increased over 2-3 years in prairies where unburned patches were left, and six out of nine specialist butterfly species were more abundant in areas with unburned patches compared to sites without them. The Karner blue butterflies actively used all 11 unburned patches surveyed within managed prairies.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3883",
    "3879"
  ]
}

