{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from 29 studies on butterfly translocation and captive-release programs shows mixed long-term success. For translocation programs (16 studies), 8 studies reported successful establishment with populations persisting 2-12 years and increasing in abundance, while 3 studies documented some populations persisting 1-49 years but others dying out within 0-7 years. A review of UK and Irish butterfly translocations found only 25% survived >3 years, 38% died out within 3 years, and only 8% survived >10 years. Large copper butterfly translocations survived up to 38 years but ultimately required supplementation. For captive-release programs (13 studies), 6 studies reported successful establishment with populations persisting 2-28 years and increasing in abundance, while 2 studies documented populations dying out 1-12 years after release. Captive-released large copper and belted beauty moth populations either died out or required ongoing supplementation. A study found only 3 of 10 captive-bred barberry carpet moth populations successfully established, with at least one persisting 5 years. Captive-bred individuals showed lower survival rates compared to wild or translocated counterparts. The evidence indicates that while some butterfly populations can be successfully re-established through these methods, long-term success rates are generally low, with many populations requiring ongoing management and supplementation to persist beyond a few years.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3909",
    "3914",
    "2476"
  ]
}

