{
  "query": "How do different methods of harvesting timber, such as selective logging and shelterwood harvesting, compare to clearcutting in their impact on moth diversity in US forests?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies in US forests, shelterwood harvesting shows better outcomes for moth diversity compared to clearcutting. One controlled, before-and-after study found that macro-moth species richness was higher after shelterwood harvesting than after patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to thinned and unharvested forests (Action ID: 3871). Another replicated, controlled study found that moth species richness recovered faster after shelterwood harvesting than after group selection harvesting or clearcutting (Action ID: 3871). \n\nFor selective logging, the results are more mixed. A replicated, controlled, before-and-after study in the USA found that forests harvested by single tree selection had similar moth species richness to clearcut forests, but lower richness than unharvested forests (Action ID: 3867). Another study found that forests managed by shelterwood harvesting had similar moth species richness to single tree harvesting and clearcutting, but lower than unharvested forest (Action ID: 3871).\n\nThinning also showed positive results, with one study finding higher macro-moth species richness after thinning compared to patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to unharvested forest (Action ID: 3868). Group selection harvesting showed similar moth species richness to clearcutting but lower than unharvested forest (Action ID: 3868).\n\nOverall, the evidence suggests that shelterwood harvesting and thinning maintain better moth diversity than clearcutting, while selective logging results are more variable and often similar to clearcutting in terms of moth species richness.",
