{
  "query": "What are the observed effects of ceasing grassland management, either by stopping mowing or grazing, on butterfly abundance and diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on multiple studies, the effects of ceasing grassland management on butterfly abundance and diversity are variable and complex. For ceasing mowing specifically, 14 studies found mixed abundance responses - 4 studies showed lower abundance compared to managed grasslands while 4 showed higher abundance, with effects varying by species type. Woodland and hedgerow butterflies increased but grassland/farmland species decreased after abandonment (action 3957). For ceasing grazing, 24 studies showed similar variability - 6 studies found higher abundance of butterflies and moths on abandoned grasslands, while 4 found lower abundance compared to grazed areas. Several studies reported that specialist species like large blue and silver-studded butterflies went extinct in some abandoned meadows (action 3956). Community composition studies indicated that abandoned grasslands became dominated by generalist butterfly species with fewer generations per year compared to managed grasslands (actions 3957, 3956). For species richness, results were equally mixed - about half of studies found similar richness between abandoned and managed grasslands, while others found either higher richness (especially for grasslands abandoned for 2-10 years) or lower richness (particularly for longer abandonment periods >10-20 years) compared to managed areas.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3957",
    "3956",
    "3961",
    "3958"
  ]
}

