{
  "query": "Over what timescales have butterfly populations been observed to respond to woodland management practices like coppicing and clearing in the UK?",
  "relevant_summary": "Butterfly populations have been observed to respond to woodland management practices over multiple timescales in the UK. For clearing/opening patches in forests, studies showed that butterfly species richness declined over the first three years after clearing, but patches cleared 2\u20134 years ago had greater abundance of heath fritillary than patches cleared 7\u201311 years ago or patches in their first year after clearance (Action ID: 3938). For coppicing woodland, studies found that the abundance of butterflies, including heath fritillary specifically, was higher in woodland coppiced 2\u20134, 5\u20137, or 12\u201315 years ago compared to woodland coppiced 5\u201311 or >15 years ago (Action ID: 3939). One study found that woodland coppiced two years ago had greater species richness of butterflies than woodland coppiced >15 years ago (Action ID: 3939). Pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations were more likely to persist for up to 20 years in woodlands with coppicing or young plantations compared to mature woodland (Action ID: 3941). These responses indicate that butterfly populations show both short-term (1\u20134 years) and medium-term (12\u201320 years) responses to woodland management, with some benefits persisting for up to two decades.",
