{
  "action_id": "697",
  "action_title": "Employ areas of semi-natural habitat for rough grazing (includes salt marsh, lowland heath, bog, fen)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nA series of site comparison studies from the UK found that areas of heathland that had been re-seeded with grass to improve livestock grazing were avoided by nesting whimbrels but were the main early spring feeding areas for them. There was no difference in whimbrel chick survival between areas of heathland re-seeded with grass and those that had not.\nTwo replicated studies from the UK found higher butterfly abundance and species richness and a higher frequency of occurrence of songbirds and invertebrate-feeding birds on areas of grazed semi-natural upland grassland than grazed improved pasture. However members of the crow family showed the opposite trend. A review found excluding cattle from fenland reduced the number of plant species, and that low-medium grazing levels could have positive effects on fenland biodiversity but may need to be accompanied by additional management such as mowing.\nOne study from the UK found northern lapwing nest survival and clutch size were greater on ungrazed than grazed marshes. A replicated site comparison from the UK found the proportion of young grey partridges was negatively associated with rough grazing (in combination with several other interventions)."
}

{
  "query": "How does managing semi-natural open habitats with rough grazing compare to using prescribed fire for butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, both rough grazing and prescribed fire management of semi-natural open habitats show mixed but generally positive effects on butterfly and moth populations, with outcomes varying by species and management intensity.\n\nRough grazing studies: Evidence from 9 studies showed that rough grazing in semi-natural habitats (salt marsh, lowland heath, bog, fen) had variable effects. Community responses showed that lightly grazed saltmarsh had different micro-moth communities than heavily grazed areas, with some studies finding similar species richness between grazed and unmanaged areas, while others found greater species richness with light grazing. Population responses were also mixed - some studies found higher butterfly abundance on grazed fenland and coastal dunes compared to unmanaged areas, while others found lower abundance on grazed meadow steppe. Light sheep grazing specifically showed higher micro-moth abundance compared to moderate/heavy grazing or no grazing. Behavior studies indicated that brown argus and Alcon large blue butterflies were more likely to occupy areas managed by cattle or pony grazing compared to unmanaged land.\n\nPrescribed fire studies: Evidence from 13 studies showed that prescribed burning in grasslands and open habitats also produced variable results. Community composition was generally similar between burned and unburned areas, though one study found lower species richness in patch-burned pastures compared to rotationally grazed ones. Population responses showed that some species (heath fritillary adults, marsh fritillary caterpillars, Fender's blue caterpillars and eggs) had higher abundance after burning, while others (Brenton blue butterfly, rosy marsh moth caterpillars, regal fritillary adults) had lower abundance on burned land. Some prairie specialists were less abundant in burned areas compared to hayed or grazed prairies, while generalist and migrant species showed higher abundance in burned areas. Leaving unburned patches during prescribed burning was beneficial, increasing abundance for 6 out of 9 specialist butterfly species.\n\nBoth management approaches showed species-specific responses, with the effectiveness depending on factors such as grazing intensity, burning frequency, and the presence of refugia (unburned patches in fire management).",
  "action_ids": [
