{
  "query": "For butterfly conservation in European farmland, how do wildflower strips compare to uncultivated or grass margins?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from multiple European studies shows that wildflower strips generally support higher butterfly abundance and species richness compared to uncultivated or standard grass margins. Wildflower strips had higher butterfly species richness than cropped fields, unsown margins, and conventional grassland, with 8 of 13 studies showing greater species richness and diversity of butterflies and moths. Ten studies found higher abundance of all butterflies, generalist butterflies and specialist butterflies in sown wildflower strips compared to conventional field margins, unsown margins, cropped fields and conventional grassland. \n\nIn comparison, uncultivated margins showed more variable results. Two of five studies found that uncultivated margins had lower species richness of butterflies than margins sown with wildflowers, while two studies found similar species richness between uncultivated and sown margins. For abundance, six of seven studies found that butterfly abundance was lower in uncultivated margins than in margins sown with wildflowers or grasses, with only one study showing higher abundance in uncultivated margins. Grass margins also showed positive effects, with three of four studies finding higher butterfly abundance than cropped field edges, and floristically enhanced grass buffers or wildflower strips having greater species richness than standard grass margins. However, wildflower strips consistently outperformed both standard grass margins and uncultivated margins for butterfly conservation.",
