{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effects of restoring post-industrial sites, like mines or brownfields, on butterfly and moth communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies evaluated the effects of restoring or creating new habitats after mining and quarrying on butterflies and moths. Two studies were in the Czech Republic, and one was in each of the UK and New Zealand. Two studies provided community response evidence: one replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found that 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) were only found on flattened spoil heaps, compared to 30% which were only found on unflattened heaps. This same study found that technically restored quarries had lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally, and flattened spoil heaps had lower species richness of moths than unflattened spoil heaps. Two studies provided population response evidence: one replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK found that on slate waste tips trees where fertilizer was applied had similar abundance of caterpillars to unfertilized trees. One site comparison study in New Zealand found that a peat bog restored after mining supported similar density and size of Fred the thread moth caterpillars to undisturbed bogs. No studies were found that evaluated the effects of protecting or restoring brownfield or ex-industrial sites on butterflies and moths.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3862",
    "3835"
  ]
}

