{
  "query": "What factors influence the success of captive breeding and release programs for butterflies and moths?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several key factors influence the success of captive breeding and release programs for butterflies and moths. Rearing conditions significantly affect outcomes, with lower densities showing higher survival rates for various species, and temperature playing a crucial role with 20\u00b0C being optimal compared to 25\u00b0C. For ant-associated species, survival varies depending on ant nest characteristics and species. Host plant quality is critical - monarch caterpillars showed different survival on different milkweed species, and some species require specific plant combinations for survival. Long-term captivity can affect butterfly condition, with populations becoming heavier but developing smaller wings over generations. Release success rates are variable, with only 25% of programs surviving >3 years and 8% surviving >10 years, often requiring continued supplementation. Captive-bred individuals frequently show lower survival than wild or translocated counterparts.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3916",
    "3914"
  ]
}

