{
  "query": "To benefit butterflies on productive grasslands, how does reducing livestock density compare with seasonal livestock removal or reducing mowing frequency?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, reducing livestock density (Action 3959) shows the strongest positive effects for butterfly conservation on grasslands. Eight studies found that grasslands with lower stocking densities had greater species richness of adult butterflies, moths, and burnet moths compared to higher stocking densities, with eight studies showing increased abundance of butterflies, moths, and caterpillars. \n\nSeasonal livestock removal (Action 3960) produced more mixed results. While three controlled studies found higher butterfly and caterpillar abundance when cattle or sheep were removed seasonally, three other studies found similar abundance compared to year-round grazing, and two studies found similar species richness.\n\nReducing mowing frequency (Action 3961) also showed mixed benefits. Two studies found higher species richness with once-yearly cutting compared to more frequent cutting, but three studies found similar abundance of butterflies regardless of cutting frequency, while two studies found higher abundance with reduced mowing.\n\nDelaying cutting/first grazing dates (Action 3967) showed positive effects in some studies, with three of four studies finding greater abundance when cutting was delayed to July or September compared to May or June cutting.",
  "action_ids": [
