{
  "query": "What are the benefits of planting new hedges and managing existing ones for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Planting new hedges and managing existing hedgerows for wildlife on farmland provides significant benefits for butterfly and moth conservation. Studies show that established hedgerows support higher species richness of butterflies and macro-moths compared to crops, pasture, and beetle banks, with hedgerows having greater species richness than grass banks between fields. The abundance of butterflies, moths, and macro-moths is consistently higher along hedgerows than in field interiors or grass margins without hedgerows. Managing hedgerows through practices like cutting every 2-3 years instead of annually, cutting in autumn rather than winter, allowing incremental growth, maintaining hedgerows with trees, and keeping hedgerows between 1-2 meters tall significantly increases the abundance and diversity of butterflies and moths. Specific management techniques that benefit Lepidoptera include hedgerows with more complex structure, those containing trees, and those with scalloped edges. These management approaches create better habitat conditions, provide nectar sources, and support higher populations of both adult butterflies and moths as well as their caterpillars and pupae.",
  "action_ids": [
