{
  "query": "What are the potential benefits and negative consequences of abandoning management on grasslands for butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 26 studies examining grazing cessation and 16 studies examining mowing cessation, abandoning management on grasslands has mixed effects on butterfly and moth populations. Benefits include: higher abundance of Scotch argus, woodland and hedgerow butterflies, and burnet moths in abandoned grasslands (Action IDs: 3956, 3957); higher species richness of butterflies and moths in some abandoned grasslands compared to commercially grazed or recently managed sites; and increased abundance of caterpillars and small insects including caterpillars. Negative consequences include: extinction of specialist species like large blue and silver-studded blue butterflies in some abandoned meadows (Action ID: 3956); lower abundance of grassland and farmland butterfly species; reduced species richness in long-abandoned (>10-20 years) grasslands; dominance of generalist species in abandoned sites with fewer generations per year; and lower abundance of some species like spring webworm caterpillars. The community composition may shift toward woodland species at the expense of traditional grassland specialists, with effects varying by abandonment duration, geographic location, and specific species requirements.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3956",
    "3957"
  ]
}

