{
  "query": "In European forests, how do the effects of coppicing and clearing patches compare for butterfly and moth communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from European forests, coppicing and clearing patches both create habitat for butterfly and moth communities, but with some key differences. Clearing patches in forests was found to increase butterfly species richness and abundance compared to unmanaged patches or closed canopy forest, as evidenced by studies showing higher general butterfly abundance and specific species increases (e.g., chequered blue, woodland brown, high brown fritillary, small pearl-bordered fritillary). However, cleared patches showed lower moth species richness than coppiced woodland or mature forest. One UK study found that larger cleared patches supported higher butterfly species richness and abundance than undisturbed forest, while another found both wider and standard width rides had similar macro-moth species richness to mature forest. Woodland coppicing also created habitat for butterflies, with studies showing higher butterfly species richness in coppiced woodland compared to unmanaged woodland, and higher abundance of butterflies generally and heath fritillary specifically. Coppiced woodlands supported different communities of moths and butterflies depending on coppice age, with recent coppice (2-4 years) generally supporting higher abundances than older coppice (>15 years). Both management techniques created habitat heterogeneity important for different species groups.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3938",
