{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation and captive-breeding programs?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from 16 studies on butterfly translocation shows mixed results. Eight studies reported successful population persistence for 2-12 years with increased abundance when butterflies were translocated to their former range, sometimes combined with habitat management. However, three studies showed some populations died out within 0-7 years despite initial increases. A review of UK and Irish translocations found only 25% survived over three years and only 8% survived over 10 years. Translocation outside known native range showed similar patterns: two of three studies reported successful establishment lasting 8-28 years, while one population died out within a year.\n\nThirteen studies on captive breeding programs also showed mixed outcomes. Six studies reported captive-bred populations persisted 2-28 years and increased in abundance, while two studies documented population die-outs within 1-12 years. One review found the same survival statistics as translocations: 25% survival over three years and 8% over 10 years. Genetic studies showed translocated populations maintained genetic diversity similar to source populations 19-69 years after release. However, survival comparisons indicated released captive-bred caterpillars had lower survival rates than wild or translocated individuals.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3909",
    "3914",
    "3911"
  ]
}

