{
  "query": "How does the scale of habitat features, such as field size and margin width, affect butterfly and moth communities on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "The scale of habitat features significantly affects butterfly and moth communities on farmland. Field size studies show that smaller fields increase both species richness and abundance of butterflies and burnet moths compared to larger fields (Action ID: 3974). Five studies found that landscapes with smaller fields had higher species richness and abundance, with one study showing increased species richness after reducing field size by increasing field edge length. Regarding margin width, wider grass margins (up to 6 m) support greater species richness and abundance of butterflies, macro-moths, and micro-moths compared to conventional width margins. Studies on grass buffer strips found that wider margins had higher species richness and abundance of habitat-sensitive species, though disturbance-tolerant species showed similar responses regardless of width (Action ID: 3982). Uncultivated margins also demonstrated scale effects, with longer or wider margins supporting higher species richness of butterflies compared to shorter, narrower, or conventional width margins (Action ID: 3981).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3974",
    "3982",
    "3981"
  ]
}
